# Introduction
The common cold is a viral infection of the upper respiratory tract. It is the most common infectious disease in humans, with an estimated 1 billion cases per year in the United States alone. The common cold is caused by a variety of viruses, including rhinoviruses, coronaviruses, respiratory syncytial virus, and parainfluenza virus. The most common symptoms of the common cold are nasal congestion, sneezing, and sore throat. The common cold is usually self-limiting, lasting 7-10 days. However, some people may experience more severe symptoms, such as fever, chills, and body aches.
The common cold is a self-limiting disease, but it can be a source of significant morbidity and mortality. The common cold is the most common cause of doctor visits and missed workdays. In addition, the common cold can lead to complications such as sinusitis, otitis media, and pneumonia. The common cold is also a major cause of antibiotic resistance. Antibiotics are often prescribed for the common cold, but they are not effective against viruses. As a result, antibiotic resistance is a major problem in the treatment of the common cold.

# Introduction
Heart failure with preserved ejection fraction (HFpEF) is a complex clinical syndrome characterized by the presence of signs and symptoms of heart failure (HF) in the absence of a reduced left ventricular ejection fraction (LVEF). It is a major public health problem, with a prevalence of 10% in the general population and 50% in patients over 70 years of age. HFpEF is associated with significant morbidity and mortality, and its prevalence is expected to increase in the coming years due to the aging of the population.
HFpEF is a heterogeneous syndrome, and its pathophysiology is not fully understood. It is characterized by a complex interplay of multiple factors, including diastolic dysfunction, myocardial stiffness, vascular stiffness, and comorbidities such as hypertension, obesity, diabetes, and atrial fibrillation. These factors contribute to the development of HFpEF and can also affect its clinical course and prognosis.
The management of HFpEF is challenging, and there is no definitive treatment for this condition. Current guidelines recommend a multidisciplinary approach, including lifestyle modifications, pharmacological therapy, and device therapy. However, the evidence supporting these recommendations is limited, and further research is needed to develop more effective treatments for HFpEF.
In this article, we will discuss the pathophysiology, clinical presentation, diagnosis, and management of HFpEF. We will also review the latest research on this condition and discuss the challenges and opportunities for future research.

# Introduction

### Background

The use of positive end-expiratory pressure (PEEP) is a common practice in anesthesia. PEEP is used to prevent atelectasis and to improve oxygenation. However, the use of PEEP is not without risks. PEEP can cause hemodynamic instability, barotrauma, and ventilator-induced lung injury. The use of PEEP is also associated with increased postoperative pulmonary complications.

### Objectives

The objective of this study is to determine the effect of PEEP on postoperative pulmonary complications in patients undergoing laparoscopic bariatric surgery.

### Research Question

In patients undergoing laparoscopic bariatric surgery, what is the effect of PEEP on postoperative pulmonary complications?

It is thought to be a result of a combination of genetic predisposition, early life experiences, and learned behaviors. The biological factors that contribute to dental anxiety include genetic predisposition, early life experiences, and learned behaviors. The psychological factors that contribute to dental anxiety include cognitive factors, such as negative beliefs and attitudes about dental treatment, and emotional factors, such as fear and anxiety.
